# **Containerize legacy ASP.NET applications in just a few clicks using AWS Migration Hub Orchestrator**

By Neeraj Handa, June 16, 2025[Amazon Elastic Container Service](https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/modernizing-with-aws/category/compute/amazon-elastic-container-service/), [AWS Migration Hub](https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/modernizing-with-aws/category/migration/aws-migration-hub/), [Compute](https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/modernizing-with-aws/category/compute/), [Containers](https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/modernizing-with-aws/category/containers/), [Technical How-to](https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/modernizing-with-aws/category/post-types/technical-how-to/), [Windows on AWS](https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/modernizing-with-aws/category/aws-on-windows/), [Permalink](https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/modernizing-with-aws/containerize-asp-net-application-using-aws-migration-hub-orchestrator/).

Customers are increasingly using containers to provide a consistent and robust environment that makes it easy to run and scale applications anywhere. Amazon Web Services (AWS) container services make it easier to manage the underlying infrastructure so you can focus on innovation.

In 2020, AWS launched [AWS App2Container](https://aws.amazon.com/app2container/) (A2C), a tool that helps customers containerize legacy ASP.NET and Java applications without changing the source code. While A2C is a very powerful tool with deep customization capabilities, customers asked for a guided experience to help them package and deploy their applications to [Amazon Elastic Container Service](https://aws.amazon.com/ecs/) (Amazon ECS) without downloading or installing additional tools like A2C.

[Template replatforming](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/migrationhub-orchestrator/latest/userguide/replatform-to-ecs.html) newly released in [AWS Migration Hub Orchestrator](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/migrationhub-orchestrator/latest/userguide/what-is-migrationhub-orchestrator.html) meet this need. You can now package and deploy ASP.NET and Java applications to Amazon ECS on[AWS Fargate](https://aws.amazon.com/fargate/), a serverless, pay-as-you-go compute engine for containers, with just a few clicks directly from the AWS Management Console.

In this article, we will see how to package and deploy an ASP.NET application running on a [Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud](https://aws.amazon.com/ec2/) (Amazon EC2) Use Microsoft Windows Server to Amazon ECS on AWS Fargate using AWS Migration Hub Orchestrator.

To package and deploy an application running on-premises to Amazon ECS on AWS Fargate, you can use a template [rehost applications on EC2](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/migrationhub-orchestrator/latest/userguide/rehost-on-ec2.html) in AWS Migration Hub Orchestrator to rehost the application to Amazon EC2, then follow the steps in this article to package and deploy the application to Amazon ECS on AWS Fargate.

## **Prerequisites**

For this tutorial, you should have the following resources:

* One [Amazon Simple Storage Service (Amazon S3) bucket](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/quickstarts/latest/s3backup/step-1-create-bucket.html) to save artifacts that AWS Migration Hub Orchestrator creates as it executes.

* One version Amazon EC2 running the ASP.NET application you want to package. This EC2 instance should be [one managed node in AWS Systems Manager](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/migrationhub-orchestrator/latest/userguide/replatform-to-ecs.html#replatform-to-ecs-prerequisites-ssm-agent) and have [instance profile role with the necessary permissions attached](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/migrationhub-orchestrator/latest/userguide/replatform-to-ecs.html#replatform-to-ecs-prerequisites-permissions-instances).

* One [Supported ASP.NET applications](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/app2container/latest/UserGuide/supported-applications.html). 

  In this article, we will use a real open source application called [nopCommerce](https://www.nopcommerce.com/en). Current versions of nopCommerce are based on ASP.NET Core. Since we want to focus on legacy ASP.NET applications built on the .NET Framework, we will use [nopCommerce version 3.90](https://github.com/nopSolutions/nopCommerce/releases/tag/release-3.90), built on .NET 4.5.1. The nopCommerce application we use in this article is installed on an Amazon EC2 instance running Windows Server 2022, IIS 10, and .NET 4.5.1.

## **Process**

To get started with AWS Migration Hub Orchestrator, visit [AWS Migration Hub console](http://console.aws.amazon.com/migrationhub) and choose **Workflow templates** to create a new workflow, as shown in Figure 1\.

![][image1]

*Hình 1 – Workflow templates in AWS Migration Hub console*

Select workflow template ***Replatform applications to Amazon ECS*** and choose **Create Workflow**(Figure 2). This workflow template is the playbook for executing the replatforming process and includes:

* Steps in the replatforming process and dependencies between them;

* Services, solutions and scripts needed to automate the replatforming step;

* Required input parameters, such as source virtual machine, application name, target container configuration, and target cluster configuration.

  ![][image2]  
  Figure 2 –*Replatform applications to Amazon ECS template*

To configure your workflow, provide the following details (Figure 3):

* Name your workflow.

* Select the AWS Region where the application to be packaged is running.

* Select the Amazon EC2 instance running your application.

* Select the Amazon S3 bucket that Migration Hub Orchestrator will use to save artifacts when executing the workflow. Note: the S3 path to save application artifacts must be prefixed with **application-transformation**. For example: **s3://my-bucket/application-transformation-app1.**

* Options: select [AWS Key Management Service key](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/migrationhub-orchestrator/latest/userguide/replatform-to-ecs.html#replatform-to-ecs-prerequisites-permissions-kms) to encrypt the resources used by this workflow.

* Optional: provide a description and tags.

  ![][image3]  
  *Figure 3 – Configuring your workflow*

Select **Next** to continue to the screen **Review and Submit**. On this screen, review the configuration and select **Create** to create a workflow. Creating a workflow takes a few minutes to complete.

Once the workflow is created, confirm that the workflow status is **Not Started** in the workflow list (Figure 4).

![][image4]

*Figure 4 – Select the workflow you created*

Select your workflow and choose **Run**(Figure 5\) to begin the step-by-step process of analyzing and packaging the application.

![][image5]

*Figure 5 – Run workflow*

The workflow consists of three steps. Let's go through each step.

### **Step 1 – Analyze**

In this step, Migration Hub Orchestrator discovers IIS websites installed on the Amazon EC2 instances that you selected when configuring the workflow. After discovery is complete, the workflow status changes to **User attention required**(Figure 6).

![][image6]

*Figure 6 – Need for user attention in Step 1 (Analysis)*

To continue, select step **1.b Select Applications for transformation and deployment** In the section **\[Actions\],** select **Change Status**, select **Completed**. (Figure 7).

![][image7]

*Figure 7 – Change status to Completed in Step 1*

In the dialog box that appears (Figure 8), select the IIS site that contains the application you want to package. If you select multiple applications to package, the default option is to create a container image for each application — this is recommended in most cases. If you want to combine multiple applications into a single container, select the appropriate option.

![][image8]

### **Step 2 – Transform**

In this step, Migration Hub Orchestrator packages the selected applications into a container image, creating a new repository in [Amazon Elastic Container Registry](https://aws.amazon.com/ecr/) (Amazon ECR) to save images, and push images to this repository. Migration Hub Orchestrator stores artifacts used to create container images in the Amazon S3 bucket you configured when creating the workflow.

This step is automatic and requires no manual action. Depending on the size of the app, this step can take up to 30 minutes. Once this step is complete, the status will change to **Complete**(Figure 9).

![][image9]

*Figure 9 – Step 2 (Conversion) in Completed state*

Confirm that Migration Hub Orchestrator has created a private repository in [Amazon ECR console](https://us-east-1.console.aws.amazon.com/ecr/repositories) with the same name as your app. In this tutorial, our app name is *is-default-web-site-17a27788*.(Figure 10\)

![][image10]

*Figure 10 – Application container image in Amazon ECR*

### **Step 3 – Deploy**

In this step, Migration Hub Orchestrator deploys the container image to an Amazon ECS cluster that you can optionally pre-configure. If you do not configure an existing cluster, Migration Hub Orchestrator automatically creates a new cluster. Before continuing, confirm that the status of the step **3.a Provide Amazon ECS deployment inputs** To be **User attention required**. To configure deployment parameters, select step **3.a Provide Amazon ECS deployment inputs**. In the \[Actions\] section, select **Status**, select **Completed**. (Figure 11\)

![][image11]

*Figure 11 – Change status to Complete in Step 3 (Deployment)*

In the dialog box that appears (Figure 12), configure the following inputs:

* VPC ID – ID of the Amazon Virtual Private Cloud (VPC) in which you want to deploy the Amazon ECS cluster.

* ECS cluster name (optional) – select an existing Amazon ECS cluster to deploy.

* ECS task execution IAM role ARN – ARN của [Amazon ECS task execution IAM role](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonECS/latest/developerguide/task_execution_IAM_role.html).

* ECS task role ARN (optional) – ARN of [Amazon ECS task IAM role](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonECS/latest/developerguide/task-iam-roles.html).

* CPU (optional) – number of CPU units to reserve for the container.

* Memory (optional) – amount of memory in GB to allocate to the container.

  ![][image12]

  *Figure 12 – Providing input parameters for the deployment process to Amazon ECS*

Select **Confirm** to continue. Migration Hub Orchestrator will perform the following actions:

1. If you haven't selected an existing cluster, Migration Hub Orchestrator creates an Amazon ECS cluster in the VPC you provide, configuring AWS Fargate as the [capacity provider.](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonECS/latest/developerguide/Welcome.html)

2. Migration Hub Orchestrator will create a [Amazon ECS task definition](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonECS/latest/developerguide/task_definitions.html) configured with values ​​you provide for the Task Execution IAM role, Task role, CPU, Memory, and the container image path stored in Amazon ECR.

3. To keep at least one or more application container instances running, Migration Hub Orchestrator creates a [Amazon ECS service](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonECS/latest/developerguide/ecs_services.html).

4. To distribute traffic evenly among the containers in your service, Migration Hub Orchestrator creates a [Application Load Balancer](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/elasticloadbalancing/latest/application/introduction.html) and configure it to [forward traffic to your application containers](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonECS/latest/developerguide/service-load-balancing.html).

These actions can take up to 30 minutes to complete. When complete, the workflow status will change to **Complete**(Figure 13).

![][image13]

*Figure 13 – Complete workflow*

If your application uses session state, note that containers are designed to be ephemeral and can be stopped or destroyed more frequently than virtual machines like Amazon EC2. This makes it more difficult to keep session state in the container. You should consider persisting session state outside the container to a high-performance data store like [Amazon ElastiCache](https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/developer/elasticache-as-an-asp-net-session-store/) or [Amazon DynamoDB](https://github.com/aws/aws-dotnet-session-provider).

Confirm that Migration Hub Orchestrator created an Amazon ECS cluster in [Amazon ECS console](https://console.aws.amazon.com/ecs/v2/clusters)(Figure 14).

![][image14]

*Figure 14 – Amazon ECS cluster*

Select the cluster name to view cluster details. In the tab **Services**, confirm that there is a service with the status **Active**(Figure 15).

![][image15]

*Figure 15 – Amazon ECS service*

Select a service name to view details of the Amazon ECS service. On the tab **Health and metrics**, confirm there is an Application Load Balancer with 1 healthy target. Select **View load balancer** to view the details of the Application Load Balancer (Figure 16\).![][image16]

*Figure 16 – Application Load Balancer Status*

The Load Balancer details page displays the VPC, Availability Zones, status, and DNS name of the load balancer. Copy the DNS name (Figure 17\).![][image17]

*Figure 17 – DNS name of Application Load Balancer*

Paste the DNS name into your browser's address bar and confirm you can access your application (Figure 18).

![][image18]

*Figure 18 – Containerized application running on Amazon ECS*

## **Cleanup**

To delete the resources created in this article, purge the stacks in [AWS CloudFormation console](https://console.aws.amazon.com/cloudformation/home) by the name of the application you created. Make sure the button **View nested** is off and **Filter status** set to Active. For the corresponding stack, select **Delete**(Figure 19\).![][image19]

*Figure 19 – Deleting an AWS CloudFormation stack*

## **Conclusion**

In this article, you used AWS Migration Hub Orchestrator to package and deploy an ASP.NET application directly from the AWS Management Console with just a few clicks. Migration Hub Orchestrator helps you package and deploy applications to Amazon ECS through a streamlined web experience without downloading or installing any tools.

For more information about Migration Hub Orchestrator's containerization capabilities, read [original document](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/migrationhub-orchestrator/latest/userguide/replatform-to-ecs.html). For a more customized containerization experience, see [AWS App2Container](https://aws.amazon.com/app2container/). To learn about deploying Windows applications to Amazon Elastic Kubernetes Service (Amazon EKS), please refer to [this blog post](https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/modernizing-with-aws/containerizing-legacy-asp-net-applications-using-aws-app2container-a2c/).

AWS has more services and more features within those services than any other cloud provider, making it faster, easier, and more cost-effective to migrate existing applications to the cloud. Give your Microsoft applications the infrastructure they need to drive the business outcomes you want.

Visit the blog[.NET on AWS](https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/dotnet/) and [AWS Database](https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/database/) for further guidance and options for your Microsoft workloads. [Contact us](https://pages.awscloud.com/MAP-windows-contact-us.html) to start your migration and modernization journey today.
